data.value: The Greek-Roman Museum in Alexandria is a significant cultural landmark dedicated to preserving and displaying artifacts from Egypt's Hellenistic and Roman periods. It is one of the oldest museums in Egypt, originally founded in 1892 by Giuseppe Botti. Recently reopened after extensive renovations, it now houses over 10,000 artifacts spanning from the 5th century BCE to the Byzantine era, highlighting the cultural blend of Egyptian, Greek, and Roman civilizations.
